		<h1 class="page-header col-xs-offset-4 col-xs-4 col-xs-offset-4">Alcohol & My Body</h1>
       
           <div class="col-xs-offset-1 col-xs-10 col-xs-offset-1"> <button type="button" class="btn btn-info" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#demo">1.	What Is Alcohol?</button>
               <div></br></div>
  <div id="demo" class="collapse">
      <div>
      <img src="resources/images/alcohol.jpg" class="img-rounded" alt="Cinque Terre" width="90%" height="65%">
          </div>
      <div>
          			 <p>Understanding how alcohol is absorbed and processed by the
						body can be useful for understanding alcohol's effects. When you
						swallow a drink, the alcohol travels to your stomach, where some
						of it is absorbed. The rest of the alcohol travels to the small
						intestine, where it is absorbed into the bloodstream. The rate of
						absorption is important, because faster absorption means getting
						drunk faster. In general, rate of absorption will be affected by
						how fast you drink, how concentrated the alcohol is (i.e.,
						straight shots will be absorbed faster than beer or mixed drinks),
						the presence of food in the stomach, and your total blood volume.
						Although absorption rate can be slowed by eating while drinking or
						by drinking less concentrated alcohol, all the alcohol will
						eventually get into your system. Once the alcohol is absorbed, it
						will travel to all parts of the body, affecting everything from
						hunger to heart rate to brain functioning. Depending on amount,
						alcohol can cause relaxation, unconsciousness, or death. 
						</p><p>
						More than 90% of alcohol in your blood is removed by your liver through a
						process called oxidation. Less than 10% of alcohol is removed
						through sweat, breath, or urine. The liver gets rid of about one
						"drink" per hour from the body, which is slower than how much
						alcohol can be put into your body. There is no way to get rid of
						the alcohol in your body faster. Coffee or cold showers will not
						sober up people-the alcohol is still there. The alcohol is
						broken down into acetaldehyde, a poison, which is rapidly
						converted into acetate, and finally into carbon dioxide and water,
						which then filters through the kidneys and eventually leave as
						urine. Alcohol broken down releases energy (calories) but does not
						have any significant nutritional value. The alcohol is often
						stored in fat in the body-this is why people talk about "beer
						bellies". One beer often has as many calories as a hot dog: six
						beers = six hot dogs.</p>
          </br>
      </div>
   
  </div>
