            <div class="col-xs-offset-1 col-xs-10 col-xs-offset-1"> <button type="button" class="btn btn-info" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#demo5">5.	What Is A Biphasic Effect? </button>
                <div></br></div>
  <div id="demo5" class="collapse">
      
      <div>
                      <p>As alcohol is consumed, people often feel two different
						effects. First, alcohol produces what feels like excitement,
						increased energy, and feelings of power . This arousal is usually
						experienced at lower blood alcohol levels as drinking is started.
						In the chart below, the curve first moves up to the positive side
						of the "feeling" scale. Over time, however, the good feelings
						begin to shift down to more unpleasant, depressant effects. People
						become less aroused. These effects are usually experienced as
						being tired, being "slowed down," or feeling unsteady. Eventually
						the feelings are worse than before a person started drinking,
						because the BAC begins to drop. This is where alcohol withdrawal
						starts, and often causes headaches, feeling sick or dizzy, and
						maybe a hangover. In the chart below, this second phase is in the
						bad part of the "feeling" scale. The good feelings go up when
						first drinking, but begin to fall once you drink heavily, and
						really fall after you stop drinking. After drinking for a while,
						people usually begin to feel tired, losing that initial high. The
						higher the BAC, the lower the feelings will go: there is no
						escaping a falling BAC and the depressant second phase of the
						alcohol response. Continued drinking leads to passing out or
						unconsciousness which is an extreme form of the depressant effect.
						The only way to minimize the second phase is to drink moderate
						amounts of alcohol and not build a high BAC. Think about your own
						experiences: More alcohol is not better, and more can hurt!</p></div>
      <h3>Biphasic Response and Tolerance </h3>
      <div>
      <img src="resources/images/alcohol5.jpg" class="img-rounded" alt="Cinque Terre" width="90%" height="65%">
          </div>
          
      <div>
                     <p>The biphasic response to alcohol also changes with tolerance.
						Remember that tolerance refers to needing to drink more to get the
						same effect, or being able to "hold your liquor." The biphasic
						response for people with high tolerance for alcohol is different
						than for people with low tolerance. Research shows that highly
						tolerant people have a much shorter good feeling phase, that the
						good feelings aren't as strong as before, and the bad feelings
						phase tends to be longer and worse. The change in biphasic
						responses due to tolerance is shown in the chart on the previous
						page. People who have drank heavily for a long time often say they
						"no longer get the good feelings like they used to." Beside,
						increased physical tolerance can cost you (literally money),
						because it takes more alcohol to feel a buzz.
						</p><p>
						Tolerance is not necessarily good for your body either.
						Tolerance means that your
						body is physically adjusting to a toxin in your system (too much
						alcohol); but that adjustment means that your body is no longer
						warning you when you have drank too much. Tolerance takes away the
						body's stoplight that warns when enough is enough.
						</p><p>
						Many cultural
						myths have developed over time on how to get sober more quickly,
						or how to avoid hangovers the next morning. Although some of the
						ideas that have been developed are creative, remember that nothing
						can speed up the processing of alcohol by the body. The metabolic
						rate remains constant. In fact, some students who drink heavily
						the night before a morning class are likely showing up to that
						class drunk because the alcohol has not yet left their bodies.
				   </p></div>
      
   
  </div>
               </div>
            
            <div class="col-xs-offset-1 col-xs-10 col-xs-offset-1"> <button type="button" class="btn btn-info" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#demo6">6. What Are Sobering Up Myths?</button>
                <div></br></div>
  <div id="demo6" class="collapse">
      <div>
      <img src="resources/images/alcohol6.jpg" class="img-rounded" alt="Cinque Terre" width="90%" height="65%">
          </div>
      <div><p>Some of the methods mentioned above can actually be
						dangerous rather than helpful. Exercising when extremely
						intoxicated could risk cardiovascular complications, perhaps
						stroke or heart attack. Vomiting, as mentioned, happens after the
						alcohol has been absorbed, and some people have died from
						asphyxiation on their own vomit when intoxicated. Drinking smartly
						is a much better alternative to ineffective methods used when a
						person has already drank too much to feel good.
						</p><p>
						A Hangover is a tell-tale sign you've over-indulged. Most symptoms are brought
						about by dehydration - such as a banging headache, nausea, feeling
						tired and sluggish. The best thing you can do is to drink plenty
						of water, each a potassium rich snack like a banana and go for a
						stroll to get some fresh air.</p></div>
      
   
  </div>
               </div>
            
            
            <div class="col-xs-offset-1 col-xs-10 col-xs-offset-1"> <button type="button" class="btn btn-info" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#demo7">7. What Are The Interactions Of Alcohol With Other Drugs ?</button>
                <div></br></div>
  <div id="demo7" class="collapse">
      <div>
      <p>Alcohol can be very dangerous when combined with some drugs.
						Alcohol can potentiate with drugs like tranquilizers, cold and
						allergy medicines, pain killers, and sleeping pills, which means
						that the effect of each is multiplied. In these cases, 1 + 1 may
						not equal 2, but 1 + 1 may equal 3 or 4. This can be quite
						dangerous. Alcohol and tranquilizers taken together, for example,
						can stop breathing and cause death. Alcohol and cold or allergy
						medicine together often cause people to get very messed up with
						very little to drink.
						</p><p>
						In other cases, alcohol can work against the
						effects of drugs, which increases tolerance for each of those
						drugs. When drinking alcohol and snorting cocaine, for example, a
						person can drink and snort a lot more than usual without noticing
						it. This is very dangerous, because too many poisons are being
						taken in, and your body cannot tell you have had too much because
						alcohol and cocaine hide the effects of each other. People have
						died using too much without even knowing it's time to stop.
						</p><p>
						Alcohol also does not get along with common medicines, such as
						cold medicine, cough syrup, antidepressant or anti-anxiety
						medication, and Ritalin. People have been to be stopped by the
						police for erratic behavior after mixing these substances with
						just a small amount of alcohol since they tend to interact with
						one another. In addition, some pain medicines can be harmful when
						taken with alcohol, such as Advil or Aleve, which can cause
						stomach bleeding, and Tylenol which can harm the liver in
						conjunction with heavy alcohol use.</p>
          </div>
      
   
  </div>
               </div>
               
               <div class="col-xs-offset-1 col-xs-10 col-xs-offset-1"> <button type="button" class="btn btn-info" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#demo8">8. Why Do Some People React Differently To Alcohol Than Others?</button>
                <div></br></div>
				  <div id="demo8" class="collapse">
				      <div>
				      	<p>Individual reactions to alcohol vary and are influenced by many factors, such as:</p>
				      	<ul>
				      		<li>Age, gender, race or ethnicity</li>
				      		<li>Physical condition (weight, fitness level, etc.)</li>
				      		<li>Amount of food consumed before drinking</li>
				      		<li>How quickly the alcohol was consumed</li>
				      		<li>Use of drugs or prescription medicines</li>
				      		<li>Family history of alcohol problems</li>
				      	</ul>
				      </div>
			  	</div>
               </div>
            
            
            
